\@writefile{lof}{\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {3.5}{\ignorespaces Drone size by dataset: the distribution of ground-truth \emph  {box} sizes ($\sqrt  {\text  {area}}$ in native pixels; a sample of up to $9{,}000$ label files per dataset, $n$ in the legend counts boxes, not frames; each histogram shows the fraction of that dataset's boxes per bin). Svanstr\"om drones (median $28$~px) sit close above the YOLOv26n \texttt  {imgsz=640} resolvable floor ($\sqrt  {\text  {area}}\approx 8$~px), with a visible sub-floor tail; small targets near the floor are where detection degrades long before the hard limit, which is why Svanstr\"om recall degrades sharply at \texttt  {imgsz=640} (baseline $0.964 \to 0.684$) and resolves at \texttt  {imgsz=1280} (floor $\approx 4$~px; Section~\ref {sec:resolution_arch}). Anti-UAV drones (median $93$~px) are an order of magnitude larger and supra-floor at either resolution.}}{37}{figure.caption.15}\protected@file@percent }
\newlabel{fig:drone_size_hist}{{3.5}{37}{Drone size by dataset: the distribution of ground-truth \emph {box} sizes ($\sqrt {\text {area}}$ in native pixels; a sample of up to $9{,}000$ label files per dataset, $n$ in the legend counts boxes, not frames; each histogram shows the fraction of that dataset's boxes per bin). Svanstr\"om drones (median $28$~px) sit close above the YOLOv26n \texttt {imgsz=640} resolvable floor ($\sqrt {\text {area}}\approx 8$~px), with a visible sub-floor tail; small targets near the floor are where detection degrades long before the hard limit, which is why Svanstr\"om recall degrades sharply at \texttt {imgsz=640} (baseline $0.964 \to 0.684$) and resolves at \texttt {imgsz=1280} (floor $\approx 4$~px; Section~\ref {sec:resolution_arch}). Anti-UAV drones (median $93$~px) are an order of magnitude larger and supra-floor at either resolution}{figure.caption.15}{}}
